WEBVTT

00:05.100 --> 00:08.040
[dramatic music]

00:08.070 --> 00:14.910
♪

00:14.940 --> 00:17.220
- It's too dangerous
for you to stay out here.

00:17.250 --> 00:18.390
I'm gonna have to extract you--

00:18.430 --> 00:19.430
- No!
- For medical reasons.

00:19.460 --> 00:20.600
- What?

00:20.640 --> 00:22.220
I wouldn't have ever believed

00:22.260 --> 00:24.090
I would only last 52 days.

00:24.120 --> 00:25.780
- All the fat is gone.

00:25.810 --> 00:27.440
I can't believe
there's another wolverine.

00:27.470 --> 00:28.820
Bad news.

00:28.850 --> 00:32.100
- Oh, my God, I got a rabbit
in my lifting pole!

00:32.130 --> 00:34.240
To have food--
what a turnaround.

00:34.270 --> 00:36.130
- There's been
a new development.

00:36.170 --> 00:37.790
My entire bay has frozen.

00:37.830 --> 00:38.900
♪

00:38.930 --> 00:41.900
[dramatic music]

00:41.930 --> 00:47.350
♪

00:47.390 --> 00:50.010
male narrator: In "Alone's"
coldest location ever,

00:50.050 --> 00:53.290
ten participants fight
to survive the Arctic.

00:53.320 --> 00:55.020
- The Arctic is one
of the most physically

00:55.050 --> 00:56.150
demanding places on Earth.

00:56.190 --> 00:57.880
- So freaking cold right now.

00:57.910 --> 01:00.160
narrator: Battling
subzero temperatures...

01:00.190 --> 01:02.510
- This climate's harsh,
it's extreme.

01:02.540 --> 01:04.200
It's mean.
It's got teeth.

01:04.230 --> 01:05.440
- Get caught out here
in a whiteout

01:05.470 --> 01:06.510
and you're in trouble.

01:06.540 --> 01:08.060
narrator: Vicious predators...

01:08.100 --> 01:09.690
- Heard something big
moving back there.

01:09.720 --> 01:12.070
- It's me against
the wolverine right now.

01:12.100 --> 01:13.340
narrator: And isolation.

01:13.380 --> 01:14.970
- There's nothing
to fill that void.

01:15.000 --> 01:17.110
It's just you left alone
with your thoughts.

01:17.140 --> 01:19.760
narrator: How long
will they endure?

01:19.800 --> 01:21.630
- House is on fire!

01:21.660 --> 01:23.910
- I'm scared,
but I don't wanna tap.

01:23.940 --> 01:27.120
- This is the most unforgiving
landscape I've ever seen.

01:27.150 --> 01:29.120
narrator: The last
one standing wins.

01:29.150 --> 01:32.260
- This environment will strip
away everything and anything

01:32.290 --> 01:33.990
you thought you had.

01:34.020 --> 01:41.030
♪

01:50.690 --> 01:55.180
♪

01:55.210 --> 01:59.290
[water gently lapping]

01:59.320 --> 02:01.250
♪

02:01.290 --> 02:03.670
- It is day 58,

02:03.700 --> 02:07.740
and it is still cold
as anything.

02:07.780 --> 02:09.540
Oh, my God.

02:09.570 --> 02:13.750
There is no mistaking
that we are in winter.

02:13.780 --> 02:16.480
The sun is up
for, like, five hours,

02:16.510 --> 02:20.170
it feels like--
of, like, real solid light.

02:20.200 --> 02:23.860
'Cause it's already
going down and it's 3:00.

02:23.900 --> 02:30.900
♪

02:33.600 --> 02:36.530
[wind whistling]

02:36.570 --> 02:37.530
♪

02:37.570 --> 02:38.840
- It's frickin' cold in here.

02:38.880 --> 02:41.020
It's well,
well below freezing.

02:41.050 --> 02:43.950
So what I'm gonna try
and do here

02:43.990 --> 02:47.960
is, um, take the hot rocks
out of the fire

02:47.990 --> 02:49.890
and lay them on two long sticks

02:49.920 --> 02:51.480
and then just slide them in.

02:51.510 --> 02:54.340
They all go in as a group
stacked on top of each other.

02:54.380 --> 02:56.550
They'll probably release
their heat more up

02:56.590 --> 02:58.830
than into the ground.

02:58.860 --> 03:01.040
Okay, that looks like
what I wanted.

03:01.070 --> 03:02.320
It worked.

03:02.350 --> 03:05.080
So long as nothing catches
the bed on fire tonight.

03:05.110 --> 03:12.120
♪

03:20.020 --> 03:22.680
- This today is what
you would call...

03:22.710 --> 03:24.230
♪

03:24.270 --> 03:25.820
Rough weather.

03:25.860 --> 03:27.200
The winter and the ice

03:27.240 --> 03:29.760
allows for very small margins
of error.

03:29.790 --> 03:33.380
[heavy breathing]

03:33.420 --> 03:35.900
Especially when you're out
in the wilderness,

03:35.930 --> 03:37.590
you have to be on your game.

03:37.630 --> 03:39.590
Like, you have a minor issue

03:39.630 --> 03:42.220
and it can lead to your death.

03:42.250 --> 03:49.220
♪

03:55.640 --> 03:57.580
[dramatic music]

03:57.610 --> 03:58.890
- We got snow.

03:58.920 --> 04:00.820
It's still coming.

04:00.860 --> 04:02.860
The Arctic winter
is like a lead blanket

04:02.890 --> 04:04.790
that is just laying on you.

04:04.830 --> 04:06.480
It penetrates you
to your core.

04:06.520 --> 04:08.170
There's nothing
that will defeat it.

04:08.210 --> 04:10.280
The heat you take
into your bag with you,

04:10.310 --> 04:12.320
once it's out, it's gone.

04:12.350 --> 04:13.630
♪

04:13.660 --> 04:15.180
I had to do sit-ups
just to try

04:15.220 --> 04:17.320
and create some body heat
in my bag.

04:17.360 --> 04:22.460
♪

04:22.500 --> 04:25.290
[ice pick thudding]

04:25.330 --> 04:28.020
♪

04:28.060 --> 04:30.540
- Water is a much
bigger task now

04:30.580 --> 04:33.230
than it was not long ago.

04:33.270 --> 04:34.510
[water splashing]

04:34.550 --> 04:38.000
All I know is it is way,
way, way cold.

04:38.030 --> 04:41.170
It feels like it dropped
30 degrees.

04:41.210 --> 04:48.210
♪

04:53.670 --> 04:56.740
- [sighs]
Okay, well...

04:56.770 --> 04:59.810
I have got some news
from the gill net.

04:59.850 --> 05:01.190
♪

05:01.230 --> 05:02.750
Here it is.

05:02.780 --> 05:04.750
Strapped to the bottom
of my pack.

05:04.780 --> 05:07.270
The ice got to the gill net,

05:07.300 --> 05:10.620
and that's where every morsel
of food I have eaten

05:10.650 --> 05:12.930
has come from.

05:12.960 --> 05:15.970
Now, that--that's all ice.

05:16.000 --> 05:18.000
I've got a little bit
of fear in me

05:18.040 --> 05:21.180
about how long I'm gonna
be here without food.

05:21.210 --> 05:22.870
But overall, I'm hoping

05:22.900 --> 05:25.350
the fear is getting
to everybody else first.

05:25.390 --> 05:32.360
♪

05:32.400 --> 05:35.360
[wind whistling]

05:35.400 --> 05:38.130
♪

05:38.160 --> 05:40.060
[rustling]

05:40.090 --> 05:41.540
♪

05:41.580 --> 05:42.720
- All right, let's show you

05:42.750 --> 05:44.510
what the inside
of my shelter looks like.

05:44.550 --> 05:45.750
♪

05:45.790 --> 05:48.340
That's--that's ice.

05:48.380 --> 05:51.240
It's just covered.

05:51.280 --> 05:53.800
That's literally
how cold it is.

05:53.830 --> 05:55.560
[exhales]

05:55.590 --> 05:57.460
I have a fire in here.

05:57.490 --> 06:00.460
Let that [bleep] sit in.
That's cold.

06:00.490 --> 06:07.500
♪

06:18.230 --> 06:25.070
♪

06:25.100 --> 06:27.140
- [sniffs]

06:30.800 --> 06:33.660
[groans]

06:35.910 --> 06:37.460
Ouch.

06:37.500 --> 06:40.460
[chuckles]

06:40.500 --> 06:42.880
[exhales]

06:42.910 --> 06:45.160
[exhales repeatedly]

06:47.090 --> 06:48.850
It's hopeless.

06:48.890 --> 06:51.230
[wind whistling]

06:51.270 --> 06:55.620
♪

06:55.650 --> 06:58.030
I have no more food options
except fishing,

06:58.070 --> 07:01.240
but the lake is frozen over.

07:01.280 --> 07:03.590
So I got a strategy
for ice fishing.

07:03.630 --> 07:05.450
I'm gonna make a fishing net,

07:05.490 --> 07:07.110
throw it in the water
under the ice--

07:07.150 --> 07:10.770
which is a trick in itself--
and then catch something.

07:10.800 --> 07:13.910
Get us started here.

07:13.950 --> 07:16.740
I've never seen anyone make
a paracord fishing net.

07:16.780 --> 07:19.470
I had to come up with
the knot myself

07:19.500 --> 07:21.130
and come up with some
little techniques,

07:21.160 --> 07:23.610
because paracord's awkward
to work with.

07:23.650 --> 07:25.680
Get it nice and tight,

07:25.720 --> 07:27.930
and then we'll do a...

07:27.960 --> 07:29.370
little hitch.

07:29.410 --> 07:30.410
♪

07:30.450 --> 07:32.100
To weave it into a net,

07:32.140 --> 07:34.480
it's a very tedious job.

07:34.520 --> 07:35.860
♪

07:35.900 --> 07:38.000
My strategy was never fishing,

07:38.040 --> 07:41.280
but that's the only option
I have here.

07:41.320 --> 07:43.390
I'm losing weight.

07:43.420 --> 07:45.810
It's physically impossible

07:45.840 --> 07:48.640
for me to win without fat,

07:48.670 --> 07:51.290
and all I can do to get fat
is fishing.

07:51.330 --> 07:53.090
This has to work.

07:53.120 --> 07:55.610
Gonna be a slow process.

07:55.640 --> 07:56.680
♪

07:56.710 --> 07:58.470
Whoo!

07:58.510 --> 08:00.100
[exhaling]

08:00.130 --> 08:02.960
It's hard to do,
and it's really cold.

08:02.990 --> 08:04.480
♪

08:04.510 --> 08:06.520
[sighs]

08:06.550 --> 08:09.380
There's one trick to surviving

08:09.410 --> 08:11.210
in super cold weather,

08:11.240 --> 08:14.010
and that is not
to let yourself get cold.

08:14.040 --> 08:15.520
You have to stay warm,

08:15.560 --> 08:17.460
which means you have
to be careful,

08:17.490 --> 08:19.150
have good gear.

08:19.180 --> 08:20.290
♪

08:20.320 --> 08:22.290
My feet are cold.

08:22.320 --> 08:24.840
[snow crunching]

08:24.880 --> 08:27.160
Man, these boots suck.

08:27.190 --> 08:28.640
[groans]

08:28.680 --> 08:30.230
As tough as you are,

08:30.260 --> 08:32.610
once you get really cold
out here,

08:32.650 --> 08:35.270
you're not tough enough
to withstand it.

08:35.300 --> 08:38.270
[wind whistling]

08:38.310 --> 08:39.480
♪

08:39.510 --> 08:41.760
Oh, my--it's too cold.

08:41.790 --> 08:43.550
Should have done this sooner.

08:43.590 --> 08:45.110
Whoo.

08:45.140 --> 08:52.080
♪

08:52.110 --> 08:55.080
[wind whistling]

08:55.120 --> 09:02.190
♪

09:07.200 --> 09:10.300
[music intensifies]

09:13.930 --> 09:16.070
- I could hear the rabbits
again last night

09:16.100 --> 09:17.590
moving around close,
and I realized

09:17.620 --> 09:19.860
it's probably because I have
all the spruce boughs around,

09:19.900 --> 09:21.760
that they're coming so close
to the cabin

09:21.800 --> 09:23.630
'cause they are all about
the spruce boughs.

09:23.660 --> 09:26.940
So it makes me really excited
to put in some close traps,

09:26.980 --> 09:29.180
'cause oh, my God,
wouldn't it be amazing

09:29.220 --> 09:31.050
to get a rabbit just--
right here,

09:31.080 --> 09:32.460
first thing in the morning?

09:32.500 --> 09:33.460
Yowza.

09:33.500 --> 09:35.090
♪

09:35.120 --> 09:37.950
Rabbits are about
and on the move,

09:37.990 --> 09:40.090
so I really need
to set more traps

09:40.130 --> 09:41.920
and check my traps.

09:41.960 --> 09:43.990
Gotta check, gotta check.

09:44.030 --> 09:46.620
[snow crunching]

09:46.650 --> 09:49.170
The true settling in
of Arctic winter

09:49.200 --> 09:51.520
happened so fast.

09:56.760 --> 09:59.350
Snow falling in the night
is bad for my trapping.

09:59.390 --> 10:02.460
Windy nights are bad
for my trapping.

10:02.490 --> 10:05.080
The mild, calm nights
where it isn't snowing,

10:05.120 --> 10:07.810
that's when I catch rabbits.

10:07.840 --> 10:10.570
And those are few
and far between anymore.

10:10.610 --> 10:11.920
♪

10:11.950 --> 10:13.570
[snow crunching]

10:13.610 --> 10:15.710
This one, nothing doing.

10:15.750 --> 10:17.580
Still set.

10:17.610 --> 10:20.300
♪

10:20.340 --> 10:23.690
I have never been
anywhere near this skinny.

10:23.720 --> 10:26.550
The hunger is definitely
starting to get to me,

10:26.590 --> 10:29.870
and when I'm really cold,
it's so hard.

10:31.180 --> 10:34.390
Fox tracks all through here.

10:34.420 --> 10:36.670
[snow crunching]

10:36.700 --> 10:38.770
Whoa!

10:38.810 --> 10:40.430
♪

10:40.460 --> 10:42.570
Check it out.

10:42.600 --> 10:45.990
This area has been
totally dug up.

10:46.020 --> 10:48.780
The fox, clearing out

10:48.820 --> 10:50.990
the rabbit areas, you guys.

10:52.850 --> 10:55.060
I wonder how many rabbits
it got?

10:55.100 --> 10:56.410
♪

10:56.440 --> 10:58.170
Wow.

10:58.200 --> 11:02.450
This area, probably done-zo.

11:02.480 --> 11:04.760
This is a good trail.

11:04.800 --> 11:07.210
And there go the fox tracks
right up there.

11:07.250 --> 11:09.220
Holy crap, man.

11:09.250 --> 11:11.110
This is rough.

11:11.150 --> 11:13.080
Uh...

11:13.120 --> 11:15.910
I really need food
really soon.

11:15.950 --> 11:16.260
♪

11:23.260 --> 11:25.920
Damn it.
[sniffs]

11:25.960 --> 11:28.370
♪

11:28.410 --> 11:31.130
Okay, well...

11:31.170 --> 11:32.790
♪

11:32.830 --> 11:35.590
I'm feeling pretty discouraged.

11:35.620 --> 11:37.690
It's very cold out.

11:37.730 --> 11:41.870
I haven't had any food
for several days now.

11:43.530 --> 11:46.740
And my weight
is going down rapidly,

11:46.770 --> 11:50.290
and they're gonna pull me soon
if I don't get food.

11:50.330 --> 11:52.360
♪

11:52.400 --> 11:55.360
Being out here
and being underfed,

11:55.400 --> 11:56.880
I think about the food

11:56.920 --> 12:00.960
that I could afford to buy
if I won a lot.

12:00.990 --> 12:02.650
Most of my life,

12:02.680 --> 12:06.030
I've not had enough money
to keep myself well-fed.

12:06.070 --> 12:09.240
That is definitely
the motivation.

12:09.280 --> 12:13.070
So desperate times call
for desperate measures.

12:16.180 --> 12:18.280
Okay, I...

12:18.320 --> 12:21.840
have these intestines
in my pot

12:21.870 --> 12:25.120
for bait for ice fishing.

12:25.150 --> 12:28.780
Now is the time
to get real humble

12:28.810 --> 12:30.780
and eat those myself.

12:30.810 --> 12:32.470
♪

12:32.510 --> 12:37.130
I'm going to skoosh out
the guts now,

12:37.170 --> 12:41.690
and then rinse again
in a fresh pot.

12:41.720 --> 12:46.280
Eating rabbit intestines
is next-level.

12:46.310 --> 12:50.140
You're eating the place
that something stores its poo!

12:50.180 --> 12:51.700
It's a lot of tissue.

12:51.730 --> 12:55.530
There's fat, there's blood,
there's muscle.

12:55.560 --> 12:56.670
♪

12:56.700 --> 12:58.320
[laughing]

12:58.360 --> 13:02.020
It looks completely,
utterly foul.

13:02.050 --> 13:04.880
♪

13:04.920 --> 13:07.610
I know,
that's thoroughly disgusting.

13:07.640 --> 13:09.400
♪

13:09.440 --> 13:11.130
I am not giving in, people.

13:11.160 --> 13:13.790
I am still trying
like anything

13:13.820 --> 13:17.210
to keep my weight up
to stay out here.

13:17.240 --> 13:18.210
[pot clinks]

13:18.240 --> 13:19.660
♪

13:19.690 --> 13:22.660
[wind whistling]

13:22.690 --> 13:25.110
I think that's
pretty well done.

13:27.010 --> 13:29.110
All right, you ready?

13:29.150 --> 13:31.220
Not sure that I am.

13:31.250 --> 13:33.320
[metal scraping]

13:33.360 --> 13:35.840
♪

13:35.880 --> 13:37.850
Hmm.

13:37.880 --> 13:40.060
It's fine.

13:40.090 --> 13:42.060
Nowhere near as gross
as you'd think.

13:42.090 --> 13:44.090
[metal scraping]

13:44.130 --> 13:51.140
♪

13:58.140 --> 14:00.110
[water roaring distantly]

14:00.140 --> 14:02.730
♪

14:02.770 --> 14:05.390
- For everybody at home...

14:05.430 --> 14:07.770
I want you to know
how hard this is.

14:09.910 --> 14:11.670
This is not, uh...

14:13.500 --> 14:17.020
This is not just
a physical challenge.

14:17.060 --> 14:20.480
It's not just
an emotional challenge.

14:20.510 --> 14:23.790
It is all the above
at maximum level.

14:23.820 --> 14:25.380
♪

14:25.410 --> 14:28.280
Your hands, even in gloves,
get cold.

14:28.310 --> 14:32.280
Then you have
the constant craving for food.

14:32.310 --> 14:36.460
Your mind just maddens you
with it.

14:36.490 --> 14:38.490
♪

14:38.530 --> 14:40.560
How long is this gonna last?

14:40.600 --> 14:41.910
♪

14:41.950 --> 14:43.390
I just wanna be home.

14:43.430 --> 14:45.430
Victorious.

14:45.470 --> 14:48.090
Holding my baby daughter.

14:48.120 --> 14:50.540
Playing with my son.

14:50.570 --> 14:53.370
Adoring my wife.

14:53.400 --> 14:55.650
Talking to family.

14:55.680 --> 14:57.510
Having friends.

15:01.070 --> 15:02.760
And you know
it'll come eventually.

15:02.790 --> 15:04.550
You just gotta keep
putting one foot in front

15:04.590 --> 15:07.350
of the other, you know?

15:07.380 --> 15:10.420
Tapping out
is just not an option.

15:10.460 --> 15:12.420
[snow crunching]

15:12.460 --> 15:16.220
Having to adapt
to an ever-changing scenario,

15:16.260 --> 15:19.780
it forces you to stay thinking
all the time about,

15:19.810 --> 15:21.330
"How do I work the problem?"

15:21.360 --> 15:22.710
You know?

15:22.740 --> 15:25.130
So I'm going to begin
getting my resources

15:25.160 --> 15:26.850
steadily rebuilt.

15:26.890 --> 15:27.960
♪

15:27.990 --> 15:30.930
Okay, so I have spoor
of a rabbit,

15:30.960 --> 15:33.410
and it keeps kind of taking
the same path,

15:33.440 --> 15:37.380
so I'm gonna make a snare
and set it on that path.

15:37.410 --> 15:39.140
The problem with
twitch-up snares

15:39.170 --> 15:42.070
in this weather is,
you bend a tree over--

15:42.110 --> 15:45.560
if it doesn't come through
in, you know, five, six days,

15:45.590 --> 15:47.490
the tree will freeze

15:47.530 --> 15:50.500
and it won't have the pop
to get it up off the ground.

15:50.530 --> 15:53.150
And by the look of the--
of the track here

15:53.190 --> 15:54.360
it's a pretty big hare,

15:54.400 --> 15:55.980
and I'm gonna need
to get it off the ground.

15:56.020 --> 15:58.780
So I'm gonna be using
a counterweight

15:58.810 --> 16:02.130
instead of using
the twitch-up method.

16:02.160 --> 16:05.580
All right, so I'm gonna fill
my stuff sack

16:05.610 --> 16:07.270
with a rock or two.

16:07.310 --> 16:08.380
♪

16:08.410 --> 16:11.450
Jeez, that was close.

16:11.480 --> 16:13.660
I know what it's like
to have nothing.

16:13.690 --> 16:16.690
I come from nothing
but hardship,

16:16.730 --> 16:19.870
tough times, and making
something out of nothing,

16:19.900 --> 16:22.670
and that's why I feel
this victory is mine.

16:22.700 --> 16:24.940
This is the big boom
in my [bleep] life.

16:24.980 --> 16:28.400
My whole life has culminated
to this point.

16:28.430 --> 16:30.290
This should be enough,
right here.

16:30.330 --> 16:31.430
♪

16:31.470 --> 16:34.510
Just put theheocks
in the stuff sack.

16:34.540 --> 16:36.890
So the big trick
is getting it

16:36.920 --> 16:39.750
to not pull my stake out
of the ground.

16:39.790 --> 16:42.760
[hammering]

16:42.790 --> 16:44.580
♪

16:44.620 --> 16:47.000
Oh, my heart's pounding.

16:47.040 --> 16:49.380
[hammering]

16:49.420 --> 16:50.800
♪

16:50.830 --> 16:54.970
Okay, so what I'd like to do
is run it over a branch

16:55.010 --> 16:57.290
and then we bring this down.

16:57.320 --> 16:59.290
♪

17:01.290 --> 17:03.980
All right, well, we'll see
how that works for me.

17:05.430 --> 17:08.880
I have my snare,
and if you follow the wire,

17:08.920 --> 17:10.960
it goes up...

17:10.990 --> 17:12.920
loops over my branches,

17:12.960 --> 17:16.380
and then comes back down
to my stuff sack.

17:16.410 --> 17:18.650
Which, you know, uh,
won't fail.

17:18.690 --> 17:21.760
It's not gonna freeze
or do anything like that.

17:21.790 --> 17:23.240
♪

17:23.280 --> 17:26.070
All right, let's get inside.

17:26.110 --> 17:27.630
[sniffs]

17:27.660 --> 17:30.630
[dramatic music]

17:30.670 --> 17:37.360
♪

17:43.130 --> 17:44.820
- Big day today.

17:44.850 --> 17:46.580
[sharp inhale]

17:46.610 --> 17:50.720
My net is finished!

17:50.750 --> 17:54.170
Loaded, weighted.

17:54.210 --> 17:57.420
Some moose meat
hanging in it.

17:57.450 --> 18:00.830
Now all that's left
is to do it, really.

18:00.870 --> 18:05.180
♪

18:05.220 --> 18:07.980
Getting ready to go
across the ice

18:08.010 --> 18:10.190
for the first time...

18:10.220 --> 18:12.740
to fish.

18:12.780 --> 18:15.540
[wind blowing]

18:15.570 --> 18:17.400
Oh, man.

18:19.540 --> 18:21.200
I'm nervous.

18:25.200 --> 18:27.860
If you go through
the ice out here,

18:27.890 --> 18:30.760
you're in huge trouble.

18:30.790 --> 18:33.420
That's something
that will kill you.

18:33.450 --> 18:38.220
But, just don't have
the options on the land.

18:38.250 --> 18:40.420
Here we are.

18:40.460 --> 18:43.320
[skis clattering]

18:43.360 --> 18:45.980
We're gonna do it here, huh?

18:46.020 --> 18:48.980
[wind howling]

18:49.020 --> 18:55.890
♪

18:55.920 --> 18:57.270
[water splashing]

18:57.300 --> 19:00.000
Don't drop your hatchet.

19:00.030 --> 19:02.070
[sighs]

19:02.100 --> 19:05.690
♪

19:05.730 --> 19:08.800
The net, you just chop
two holes in the ice

19:08.830 --> 19:11.420
about the distance apart
that the net is long.

19:11.460 --> 19:14.180
And then you find a stick
that's also that long,

19:14.220 --> 19:17.190
and you tie a long string
to that stick

19:17.220 --> 19:20.150
and you feed it under
from one hole to the other.

19:20.190 --> 19:21.160
[ice sloshes]

19:21.190 --> 19:24.400
See if we can hit
our target.

19:24.430 --> 19:27.400
[wind blowing]

19:27.440 --> 19:28.710
♪

19:28.750 --> 19:30.410
Oh, I see it right here.

19:30.440 --> 19:31.820
♪

19:31.860 --> 19:33.310
Pull it up through
the second hole

19:33.340 --> 19:36.100
and then you have a string
passed under the ice.

19:36.140 --> 19:39.450
That's where your net's tied
and you--like a laundry line

19:39.480 --> 19:41.490
pull it through
under the ice.

19:41.520 --> 19:43.180
Feeding the net under.

19:43.210 --> 19:44.350
♪

19:44.390 --> 19:47.420
Now go get a bunch of snow

19:47.460 --> 19:51.190
and dump on these holes
so they don't freeze solid.

19:52.500 --> 19:54.500
Wouldn't call that easy.

19:54.530 --> 19:56.880
It's kind of more energy
than I wanted to spend,

19:56.910 --> 20:00.640
but it's my only chance
to re-up my fat.

20:00.680 --> 20:03.020
That's what you need to do
to survive out here.

20:03.060 --> 20:04.370
♪

20:04.410 --> 20:05.610
Hope I catch a fish.

20:08.890 --> 20:11.860
[dramatic music]

20:11.900 --> 20:18.900
♪

20:23.080 --> 20:29.330
♪

20:31.290 --> 20:33.400
[fabric rustling]

20:33.430 --> 20:35.020
- [sighs]

20:35.060 --> 20:37.990
That's all the debris
from all the debris piles

20:38.020 --> 20:40.920
up against the back end
of the shelter there.

20:40.960 --> 20:44.270
So when that gets a foot
of snow on it, man,

20:44.310 --> 20:47.660
it'll be impenetrable
by the weather,

20:47.690 --> 20:50.550
so hopefully that logic is true

20:50.590 --> 20:52.350
and pays off.

20:52.380 --> 20:54.320
It's gonna get colder
and colder,

20:54.350 --> 20:57.180
and that's what I need
to be prepared for.

20:57.220 --> 21:01.150
I do think that my gill net
going under the ice will work.

21:01.190 --> 21:03.640
That gill net
is why I'm still here

21:03.670 --> 21:05.950
and potentially,
ice fishing is why

21:05.980 --> 21:08.540
I'm gonna still be here.

21:08.570 --> 21:10.570
♪

21:10.610 --> 21:12.060
[grunts]
So this is the pole

21:12.090 --> 21:13.850
I'm gonna hang the net on.

21:13.890 --> 21:15.200
♪

21:15.230 --> 21:16.860
Switching to lighter weight

21:16.890 --> 21:20.650
'cause I want this thing
to dangle more freely, um,

21:20.690 --> 21:23.860
so it'll tangle a fish
more easily.

21:23.900 --> 21:26.450
I used old nails
and tin can lids

21:26.490 --> 21:29.350
and stuff I found
some months back.

21:29.390 --> 21:30.870
♪

21:30.910 --> 21:32.670
And there we have it.

21:32.700 --> 21:35.700
In the morning,
I'm gonna deploy that.

21:35.740 --> 21:39.640
I'll tie off, um, a T-bar

21:39.670 --> 21:41.880
to the end of this thing,

21:41.920 --> 21:43.540
and that's what I'll lower it
all the way

21:43.570 --> 21:45.020
into the water with.

21:45.060 --> 21:46.230
♪

21:46.270 --> 21:48.850
It'll be good to go, so...

21:48.890 --> 21:50.990
♪

21:51.030 --> 21:54.000
Hopefully that works out.

21:54.030 --> 22:01.110
♪

22:04.460 --> 22:06.350
- Nothing in my trap,
which is expected.

22:06.390 --> 22:07.700
Not much is gonna be
moving around

22:07.740 --> 22:10.530
in this kind of cold weather.

22:10.570 --> 22:12.810
There's no real opportunities
here at my place.

22:12.840 --> 22:16.090
[sniffing]

22:17.920 --> 22:19.570
Besides me.
[laughs]

22:19.610 --> 22:21.340
But even now,
I don't know

22:21.370 --> 22:23.270
how much they'd actually get
off my bones.

22:23.300 --> 22:24.990
[laughs]

22:25.030 --> 22:27.410
It wouldn't be much
of a meal.

22:27.440 --> 22:29.170
[laughs]

22:29.200 --> 22:31.380
And even getting things
like water now

22:31.410 --> 22:34.040
are more demanding,
more taxing.

22:34.070 --> 22:36.210
If you want water,
you have to get snow,

22:36.250 --> 22:39.390
process wood, start a fire,
melt the snow.

22:39.420 --> 22:42.050
Lot of work
for a little drink of water.

22:42.080 --> 22:43.700
♪

22:43.740 --> 22:46.360
So there's a lake
on the other side of my island

22:46.390 --> 22:48.400
and it's, um--it's not frozen.

22:48.430 --> 22:51.400
I'm considering
spanning that gap

22:51.430 --> 22:53.570
and fetching water
on the other side,

22:53.610 --> 22:57.130
but to do that,
I really gotta be careful.

22:57.160 --> 22:59.720
So I'm going to use
these poles

22:59.750 --> 23:01.620
just to make some...

23:01.650 --> 23:02.890
♪

23:02.930 --> 23:05.410
Long-type snow shoes to...

23:05.450 --> 23:06.520
♪

23:06.550 --> 23:08.730
Disperse my weight.

23:08.760 --> 23:10.760
♪

23:10.800 --> 23:12.210
The only thing
keeping me going

23:12.250 --> 23:13.630
is the love of my family.

23:13.660 --> 23:16.040
That is the truth
of the matter right there.

23:16.080 --> 23:19.390
I wanna be able
to get a house, not rent.

23:19.430 --> 23:20.980
I wanna pay off our debts.

23:21.020 --> 23:24.670
I wanna take stress
off my wife.

23:24.710 --> 23:25.990
I need this, man.

23:26.020 --> 23:27.710
Like, it's not a matter
of just want.

23:27.750 --> 23:30.060
My family needs this.

23:30.090 --> 23:33.920
♪

23:33.960 --> 23:35.480
Hello?

23:35.510 --> 23:39.620
♪

23:39.650 --> 23:41.690
Thought I heard speaking.

23:41.730 --> 23:43.280
♪

23:43.310 --> 23:45.870
This is hard, people.

23:45.900 --> 23:49.980
Trying not to think about
my wife and kids right now.

23:50.010 --> 23:53.770
♪

23:53.810 --> 23:57.500
When I do get across
to the island,

23:57.530 --> 23:59.290
I'm gonna sit there and drink.

23:59.330 --> 24:00.640
♪

24:00.680 --> 24:03.230
And drink, and drink,

24:05.990 --> 24:07.890
[sniffs]

24:07.920 --> 24:14.900
♪

24:14.930 --> 24:17.140
I do feel better...

24:17.170 --> 24:18.830
being on these poles.

24:18.870 --> 24:22.560
♪

24:22.590 --> 24:26.080
Just need them
to get me across that span,

24:26.110 --> 24:27.880
where it's most dangerous.

24:27.910 --> 24:29.320
♪

24:29.360 --> 24:31.810
My face hurts.
[sniffs]

24:31.840 --> 24:32.980
♪

24:33.020 --> 24:35.470
So tired.

24:35.500 --> 24:37.820
So thirsty.

24:37.850 --> 24:39.440
[bleep] starving.

24:39.470 --> 24:40.780
♪

24:40.820 --> 24:43.170
Dehydration will put an end
to you out here

24:43.200 --> 24:46.170
just as fast
as anything else will.

24:46.200 --> 24:49.830
♪

24:49.860 --> 24:51.590
Look at that sweet,
sweet water.

24:51.620 --> 24:54.520
♪

24:54.560 --> 24:56.560
[water splashing]

24:58.600 --> 25:00.050
[exhales noisily]

25:00.080 --> 25:02.050
Oh!

25:04.570 --> 25:06.120
It's been over 24 hours

25:06.150 --> 25:08.500
since I've had anything
to drink, man.

25:10.640 --> 25:12.510
Man.

25:12.540 --> 25:15.300
This is kicking my ass!

25:15.340 --> 25:16.680
[sniffs]

25:18.100 --> 25:23.900
♪

25:23.930 --> 25:27.110
I just want my wife
and kids, man.

25:27.140 --> 25:28.690
♪

25:28.730 --> 25:33.290
[sobbing]
This is so [bleep] hard, man!

25:33.320 --> 25:36.250
I'm starving!

25:36.290 --> 25:38.950
It hurts!

25:38.980 --> 25:41.120
[sobbing]

25:41.160 --> 25:42.920
♪

25:42.950 --> 25:44.120
Please!

25:44.160 --> 25:45.400
♪

25:45.440 --> 25:47.580
Put the fight in me again!

25:47.610 --> 25:49.340
♪

25:49.370 --> 25:53.030
Put the [bleep] fight in me!

25:53.060 --> 25:55.580
♪

25:55.620 --> 25:57.240
[sobbing]

26:00.420 --> 26:03.450
[dramatic music]

26:03.490 --> 26:09.490
♪

26:10.670 --> 26:12.600
[ominous whooshing]

26:12.640 --> 26:18.500
♪

26:20.370 --> 26:23.400
- I have smoke streaming out
from underneath my bed

26:23.440 --> 26:26.650
from the hot rocks that I put
under there last night.

26:26.680 --> 26:28.440
I think that
they are smoldering.

26:28.480 --> 26:30.450
The ground has now
dried out enough.

26:30.480 --> 26:32.860
It was icy when I first
started doing this,

26:32.900 --> 26:35.280
and it's had enough time

26:35.310 --> 26:37.420
from all the nights
of me doing that

26:37.450 --> 26:41.010
to dry things out so that they
would continue to--to smolder.

26:41.040 --> 26:43.150
And I've been smelling
the smoke all night

26:43.180 --> 26:45.810
thinking it was from the fire,
but it wasn't.

26:45.840 --> 26:47.640
So I'm gonna get
underneath there

26:47.670 --> 26:50.740
and see if I can't figure out
what's going on

26:50.780 --> 26:54.920
and maybe even potentially
harvest an ember or two

26:54.950 --> 26:56.440
to relight my fire

26:56.470 --> 26:58.580
so I don't have to
do bow-drill today.

26:58.610 --> 26:59.610
[light clicks]

27:01.300 --> 27:03.100
Underneath that rock,
it's all hollowed out.

27:03.130 --> 27:04.450
It's all burned away.

27:04.480 --> 27:07.310
There's smoke coming
from the ground right here.

27:07.340 --> 27:08.620
Was hoping to get right out

27:08.660 --> 27:11.310
and deal with the gill net
this morning, but...

27:11.350 --> 27:13.520
I have to deal with
this first thing.

27:13.560 --> 27:16.180
Can't burn down my bed
and my shelter.

27:16.220 --> 27:17.670
♪

27:17.700 --> 27:20.500
Beautiful, they all came out
in one.

27:20.530 --> 27:21.950
Here we go.

27:21.980 --> 27:26.330
♪

27:26.360 --> 27:28.810
Awesome, okay.

27:28.850 --> 27:31.090
♪

27:31.130 --> 27:33.790
That was easier to do than
most of my bow-drill fires

27:33.820 --> 27:37.720
I've had to do out here,
so I'll take it.

27:37.750 --> 27:39.690
I'm going to, uh...

27:39.720 --> 27:41.000
♪

27:41.030 --> 27:43.860
Get my gill net deployed
out on the lake today.

27:43.900 --> 27:46.830
[ice cracking]

27:46.870 --> 27:49.700
♪

27:49.730 --> 27:51.530
I don't know if you can
hear that or not,

27:51.560 --> 27:55.120
but the lake is shifting
underneath us.

27:57.360 --> 27:58.780
Hopefully it's deep enough.

27:58.810 --> 28:02.190
If I can get 5 feet of depth,
I think that'll work.

28:02.230 --> 28:04.020
[ice clattering]

28:04.060 --> 28:05.580
♪

28:05.610 --> 28:08.960
I got to thinking about,
you know, my grandfather Jack.

28:08.990 --> 28:11.060
He taught me how to hunt
and fish.

28:11.100 --> 28:12.690
I'm trying to hatch a plan

28:12.720 --> 28:15.100
to take him out ice fishing.

28:15.140 --> 28:17.380
It's like one of his
favorite activities.

28:17.410 --> 28:19.830
It's been decades
since I've been out with him,

28:19.870 --> 28:21.760
fishing or hunting.

28:21.800 --> 28:23.420
These last 20 years,

28:23.460 --> 28:25.730
I've been living
far, far from home,

28:25.770 --> 28:27.800
and I haven't seen him
nearly enough

28:27.840 --> 28:30.880
because I've been too poor
to afford even a bus ticket,

28:30.910 --> 28:33.220
let alone a plane ticket.

28:33.260 --> 28:36.500
The fact that it will be
possible when I win this,

28:36.540 --> 28:39.750
I'm gonna kind of use it
as fuel to keep going.

28:39.780 --> 28:41.440
Okay.

28:41.470 --> 28:43.230
There's the channel.

28:43.270 --> 28:44.440
Chopped through.

28:44.480 --> 28:46.960
It's probably 8 or 9
inches thick.

28:47.000 --> 28:49.380
[wind blowing]

28:51.380 --> 28:53.660
Okay, she's in.

28:55.110 --> 28:57.210
Yeah, that looks beautiful.

28:57.250 --> 28:59.800
I think it's doing its job.

28:59.840 --> 29:01.530
Gill net's in the hole.

29:01.560 --> 29:04.600
Keep my fingers crossed that
some fish drifts through there

29:04.630 --> 29:06.530
and gets hung up.

29:06.570 --> 29:07.910
♪

29:07.950 --> 29:10.330
[shuffling]

29:10.360 --> 29:12.680
Yeah, I felt
pretty damn depleted today

29:12.710 --> 29:14.920
after getting off the ice.

29:14.960 --> 29:17.410
All that chopping I did
was a bit much.

29:17.440 --> 29:19.930
I pushed myself a little bit,
and I shouldn't have.

29:19.960 --> 29:22.200
I'm gonna get more efficient
out on the ice

29:22.240 --> 29:23.580
and make sure
I'm doing everything

29:23.620 --> 29:25.830
as smoothly and efficiently
as I can.

29:25.860 --> 29:28.760
And that's how I've made it
this far, so--

29:28.800 --> 29:30.660
I'm really hoping
it winds down, though,

29:30.690 --> 29:32.970
because I am...
[sniffs]

29:33.010 --> 29:34.320
Depleted.

29:34.350 --> 29:38.740
And I miss home,
and I miss my woman,

29:38.770 --> 29:41.290
and, um...

29:41.330 --> 29:43.050
you know, I'm really homesick.

29:43.090 --> 29:45.810
For the first time in my life,
actually, I'm homesick.

29:45.850 --> 29:50.130
I just have too [bleep] much
on the line out here.

29:50.160 --> 29:51.370
Too many ideas.

29:51.410 --> 29:54.480
Too many plans that, um...

29:54.510 --> 29:55.820
♪

29:55.860 --> 29:58.310
That I can't let go of.

29:58.340 --> 30:00.140
I don't think I can tap out.

30:00.170 --> 30:02.420
I just don't have it in me.

30:02.450 --> 30:09.460
♪

30:17.910 --> 30:20.920
[wind howling]

30:23.850 --> 30:25.890
- Hmm.

30:28.300 --> 30:30.480
See how my, uh--

30:30.510 --> 30:33.270
see how my hairline's
doing here.

30:33.310 --> 30:35.760
Am I losing hair
from malnutrition?

30:35.790 --> 30:38.940
Looks like--
you know, it's thin.

30:38.970 --> 30:40.830
It's a little thin.

30:44.630 --> 30:46.870
[long exhale]

30:46.910 --> 30:49.880
[wind whistling]

30:49.910 --> 30:53.360
I'm gonna go pull up
my fishing net.

30:53.400 --> 30:55.160
♪

30:55.190 --> 30:56.880
Spent a lot of energy

30:56.920 --> 30:59.890
trying to get that net
in the ice.

30:59.920 --> 31:01.990
Hopefully catch something.

31:02.030 --> 31:03.240
♪

31:03.270 --> 31:05.380
Can tell I'm not getting
enough nutrients

31:05.410 --> 31:07.380
'cause I'm tired a lot.

31:07.410 --> 31:08.970
♪

31:09.000 --> 31:12.180
In a dire situation.

31:12.210 --> 31:13.590
I need fat.

31:13.630 --> 31:16.040
I'm gonna, at some point,
just get too thin

31:16.080 --> 31:17.350
and have to go home.

31:17.390 --> 31:19.420
[sniffs]
Okay.

31:19.460 --> 31:20.530
♪

31:20.560 --> 31:22.740
Gotta catch a couple fish.

31:22.770 --> 31:24.980
[dramatic music]

31:25.020 --> 31:27.640
See if I have any luck.

31:27.670 --> 31:29.850
♪

31:29.880 --> 31:31.400
[grunts]

31:31.440 --> 31:35.340
♪

31:35.370 --> 31:36.990
Holy cow!

31:37.030 --> 31:38.240
♪

31:38.270 --> 31:40.000
Yeah!

31:40.030 --> 31:41.620
♪

31:41.650 --> 31:43.690
Whoa!

31:43.720 --> 31:45.140
We're not done...
[laughs]

31:45.170 --> 31:48.180
Not done putting notches
on our hatchet yet!

31:48.210 --> 31:49.700
♪

31:49.730 --> 31:52.280
Yeah, here we are.

31:52.320 --> 31:55.810
Look at that, we have
the same look on our face.

31:55.840 --> 31:58.290
[heavy breathing]

31:58.330 --> 32:00.120
♪

32:00.150 --> 32:01.950
[wind whistling]

32:01.980 --> 32:04.370
Let me gut this guy
really quick.

32:04.400 --> 32:07.200
Some good fat on this one.

32:07.230 --> 32:08.680
♪

32:08.710 --> 32:10.650
Good fat.

32:10.680 --> 32:11.820
♪

32:11.860 --> 32:13.930
[munches noisily]

32:13.960 --> 32:15.830
And eat it.

32:15.860 --> 32:18.240
♪

32:18.280 --> 32:20.280
I've been dreaming
of catching a fish

32:20.310 --> 32:23.450
after all the creative energy
that happened

32:23.490 --> 32:24.870
in making this net.

32:24.900 --> 32:26.910
To actually put it in the ice,

32:26.940 --> 32:29.630
catch something this valuable,

32:29.670 --> 32:32.460
it's actually shifted
my whole perspective

32:32.500 --> 32:33.810
on being out here.

32:33.840 --> 32:35.220
Starting to have hope

32:35.260 --> 32:37.260
that it might
get me somewhere.

32:37.300 --> 32:38.780
♪

32:38.810 --> 32:39.990
Whoo!

32:43.890 --> 32:46.860
[dramatic music]

32:46.890 --> 32:53.900
♪

32:58.040 --> 33:00.900
[wind whistling]

33:00.940 --> 33:03.770
- All right, end of an era.

33:03.800 --> 33:06.360
♪

33:06.390 --> 33:09.430
I am taking down
my laundry line.

33:10.810 --> 33:13.020
Pretty much wearing...

33:13.060 --> 33:16.020
all of my long underwear layers

33:16.060 --> 33:19.030
at this point, so...

33:19.060 --> 33:20.890
Doesn't really seem like
there's much point

33:20.920 --> 33:23.070
in an outdoor laundry line
anymore.

33:23.100 --> 33:26.280
But it was awfully nice to have
for a little while there.

33:26.310 --> 33:28.830
Made it feel very homey,
don't you know?

33:28.860 --> 33:31.520
All right,
so now I can pack this

33:31.560 --> 33:34.660
into the traps pack

33:34.700 --> 33:37.700
and it is time to head out
into the world

33:37.730 --> 33:42.050
with some extra cordage.

33:42.080 --> 33:45.640
♪

33:45.670 --> 33:47.330
Let's go check traps.

33:47.370 --> 33:48.680
♪

33:48.710 --> 33:51.710
You've got to keep
the calories coming in

33:51.750 --> 33:53.680
when it is so cold.

33:53.720 --> 33:55.100
♪

33:55.130 --> 33:57.030
It's getting more
and more cold

33:57.060 --> 33:59.100
and I have less
and less reserves.

33:59.140 --> 34:02.520
The intestines
were the last resort.

34:02.550 --> 34:04.070
Basically, I could get pulled

34:04.110 --> 34:06.450
if I don't start getting
more food soon.

34:06.490 --> 34:08.870
[animal squeaking]

34:08.900 --> 34:12.220
Please, please,
please, rabbits.

34:12.250 --> 34:14.500
Please, please, please.

34:14.530 --> 34:15.980
♪

34:16.010 --> 34:17.500
Let's see.

34:17.530 --> 34:18.910
♪

34:18.950 --> 34:21.920
Nothing here.

34:21.950 --> 34:23.470
[rustling]

34:23.500 --> 34:25.440
All right, I can see--
[gasps]

34:25.470 --> 34:27.300
No way!

34:27.340 --> 34:31.030
[gasps]
I got a squirrel!

34:31.060 --> 34:33.340
Hooray, thank God!

34:33.380 --> 34:35.520
Yes!

34:35.550 --> 34:37.930
Thank you, dear squirrel.

34:37.970 --> 34:40.560
Okay.
[sniffs]

34:40.590 --> 34:42.630
Here is my squirrel.

34:42.660 --> 34:44.870
I got a squirrel to eat today.

34:44.910 --> 34:46.040
Hooray!

34:46.080 --> 34:47.770
Now I'm way more enthused

34:47.800 --> 34:51.050
to go check the rest
of my traps than I have been.

34:51.080 --> 34:53.190
This is so much better

34:53.220 --> 34:56.810
than frozen rabbit guts
right now.

34:56.850 --> 34:58.300
Yes.

34:58.330 --> 35:01.370
[percussive music]

35:01.400 --> 35:03.890
♪

35:03.920 --> 35:07.100
No freaking way.

35:07.130 --> 35:08.830
Check it out.

35:08.860 --> 35:11.550
Another squirrel.

35:11.590 --> 35:14.870
Ugh! Yay!

35:14.900 --> 35:17.520
The home trap's...
[sniffs]

35:17.560 --> 35:20.110
the most effective today.

35:20.150 --> 35:21.560
[snow crunching]

35:21.600 --> 35:23.530
Oh, my God.

35:23.560 --> 35:26.740
I just got another squirrel

35:26.770 --> 35:28.850
in my close home trap.

35:28.880 --> 35:30.610
Check it out.

35:30.640 --> 35:33.850
I am so grateful, you guys.

35:33.890 --> 35:36.890
I am gonna eat enough today.

35:36.920 --> 35:40.370
I am going to get
enough calories.

35:40.410 --> 35:43.170
That is freaking amazing.

35:43.210 --> 35:45.620
Everything is possible again,

35:45.660 --> 35:50.140
and it's so time
for a woman to win this.

35:50.180 --> 35:53.150
[dramatic music]

35:53.180 --> 35:59.880
♪

36:06.750 --> 36:10.960
♪

36:15.060 --> 36:18.520
- I'm starving out here.

36:18.550 --> 36:21.450
I've lost a lot of weight.
[sniffles]

36:21.480 --> 36:24.450
[fire crackling]

36:24.490 --> 36:30.740
♪

36:30.770 --> 36:33.460
My brain's [bleep] up.

36:33.500 --> 36:37.980
♪

36:38.020 --> 36:40.430
Today is med check.

36:40.470 --> 36:42.130
I hope they say I'm all right.

36:42.160 --> 36:44.130
It's just something
that, you know, I can--

36:44.160 --> 36:46.920
I can push through
if I choose to.

36:46.960 --> 36:48.930
♪

36:48.960 --> 36:51.270
You put a price on my life,

36:51.310 --> 36:54.410
right now it's a $1/2 million.

36:54.450 --> 36:58.350
And what I'm hoping is that
whoever's still out here

36:58.380 --> 37:00.040
has less than me
and less weight

37:00.070 --> 37:01.560
and I can just ride it out.

37:01.590 --> 37:02.840
♪

37:02.870 --> 37:04.360
For all I know,

37:04.390 --> 37:07.700
the other guy could be
leaving tomorrow.

37:07.740 --> 37:10.330
So, you know, every day
could be the day you win.

37:10.360 --> 37:11.330
♪

37:11.360 --> 37:13.120
[distant helicopter whirring]

37:13.160 --> 37:15.330
Here they come.

37:15.370 --> 37:17.580
♪

37:17.610 --> 37:20.370
Fingers crossed
for good news, okay?

37:20.410 --> 37:23.410
♪

37:23.440 --> 37:26.270
[snow crunching]

37:26.310 --> 37:27.960
♪

37:28.000 --> 37:30.280
- So do you have any symptoms
that I should be aware about?

37:30.310 --> 37:32.280
- No, just, uh--
well, I don't know.

37:32.310 --> 37:33.730
I'm just sore, man.

37:33.760 --> 37:35.940
- Let's give your heart
and lungs a listen.

37:35.970 --> 37:38.350
- [deep inhale]

37:38.390 --> 37:39.700
♪

37:39.740 --> 37:42.120
- One more.
- [deep inhale]

37:42.150 --> 37:48.190
♪

37:48.230 --> 37:50.370
[bleep].

37:50.400 --> 37:51.750
♪

37:51.780 --> 37:53.750
[sighs]
- And step off.

37:53.780 --> 37:55.300
- Ugh.

37:55.340 --> 37:56.990
- And turn around real quick.
Real quick.

37:57.030 --> 37:58.240
♪

37:58.270 --> 38:00.000
And go back inside.

38:00.030 --> 38:01.240
♪

38:08.760 --> 38:10.870
- You push yourself out here.

38:10.900 --> 38:14.490
You're really trying
to go for it, you know?

38:14.530 --> 38:19.530
♪

38:22.920 --> 38:24.260
- Just hit me with it, man.

38:24.300 --> 38:25.850
Don't waste any time.

38:29.300 --> 38:30.920
- [bleep], man.

38:30.960 --> 38:33.340
Man, come on.

38:33.380 --> 38:35.830
♪

38:35.860 --> 38:38.170
I feel fine, I'm just beat up.

38:38.210 --> 38:39.760
I-I don't understand.

38:43.250 --> 38:44.560
♪

38:44.590 --> 38:47.250
- This is the worst news
you could have told me.

38:47.290 --> 38:48.250
♪

38:48.290 --> 38:51.220
Why is this happening to me?

38:51.250 --> 38:53.460
This can't be right.

38:53.500 --> 38:55.400
♪

38:55.430 --> 38:57.160
This can't be right.

38:57.190 --> 38:58.330
♪

39:00.440 --> 39:03.720
- [sighs]
How much of a danger zone?

39:03.750 --> 39:06.170
- Once your body stops
eating its own fat,

39:06.200 --> 39:07.720
it starts consuming
its own muscle.

39:07.750 --> 39:09.690
- That's right.
That's--I know this.

39:09.720 --> 39:11.140
I know this.

39:11.170 --> 39:13.930
- And among the muscle
it's consuming is heart muscle.

39:13.970 --> 39:15.520
Liver, kidney.

39:18.630 --> 39:23.220
♪

39:23.250 --> 39:25.220
[hushed breath]

39:25.250 --> 39:28.050
♪

39:28.080 --> 39:30.160
- Oh, my God, dude.

39:30.190 --> 39:31.880
I can't lose this
for my family.

39:31.920 --> 39:34.330
Oh, my God, dude.

39:34.370 --> 39:36.370
I can't lose this
for my family.

39:38.790 --> 39:42.890
- We are worried about
possible cardiac complications,

39:42.930 --> 39:44.410
and worried if you continue

39:44.450 --> 39:46.520
you may make prolonged damage
to your heart.

39:46.550 --> 39:48.240
- I don't want to do that.

39:48.280 --> 39:51.830
♪

39:51.870 --> 39:54.080
My family would rather
have me alive, right?

39:54.110 --> 39:55.530
[laughs]

39:55.560 --> 39:58.180
♪

39:58.220 --> 40:00.290
Least I can say
I gave it hell.

40:00.320 --> 40:04.780
♪

40:04.810 --> 40:07.500
I didn't get the victory
this time, baby.

40:07.540 --> 40:08.850
♪

40:08.880 --> 40:11.060
I know I made a promise.

40:11.090 --> 40:12.340
♪

40:12.370 --> 40:14.130
I'm sorry.

40:14.170 --> 40:15.680
♪

40:15.720 --> 40:18.860
I had every intention
of leaving either victorious

40:18.890 --> 40:20.030
or in a bag.

40:20.070 --> 40:21.970
I'm realizing I'm closer
to the bag

40:22.000 --> 40:24.310
than I am to the victory.

40:24.350 --> 40:26.350
It hurts to know it's over.

40:26.380 --> 40:28.700
You just wanna give
your family the security

40:28.730 --> 40:31.390
you never had,
and that's why I took this on.

40:31.420 --> 40:32.430
♪

40:32.460 --> 40:35.220
You give everything you got.

40:35.260 --> 40:37.780
And normally your best
is enough.

40:37.810 --> 40:39.470
It has been in the past.

40:39.500 --> 40:41.740
But this time, it wasn't.

40:41.780 --> 40:44.510
It's a hard realization
to, uh--

40:44.540 --> 40:45.710
to know that you're gonna have

40:45.750 --> 40:47.890
to face the people
you let down.

40:47.920 --> 40:49.820
They deserve a hero
in their life,

40:49.860 --> 40:51.370
and it's hard to realize

40:51.410 --> 40:53.760
you're not the hero
of this story.

40:53.790 --> 40:55.790
And that's a hard pill
to swallow.

40:55.830 --> 40:57.140
♪

40:57.170 --> 40:59.760
[dramatic music]

40:59.800 --> 41:01.040
- [bleep].

41:01.070 --> 41:02.800
I just ripped the heck
out of it.

41:02.830 --> 41:04.910
I might have just totally
ruined my gill net.

41:04.940 --> 41:07.630
- [bleep].
It's really, really thick.

41:07.670 --> 41:11.120
If I can't get fish,
I don't know what I can do.

41:11.150 --> 41:14.670
- I left the ladder up.
[groans loudly]

41:14.710 --> 41:16.230
I can't protect my meat.

41:16.260 --> 41:18.370
At this point, I'm just done.

41:18.400 --> 41:24.960
♪

41:24.990 --> 41:26.860
[fire roars intensely]

41:26.890 --> 41:28.690
[high-pitched ringing]

41:28.720 --> 41:30.590
[suspenseful music]
